          "body": "Verse 2 anatomizes something far subtler than outward sin: the psalmist describes a man who flatters himself 'in his own eyes concerning the discovery of his iniquity and the hatred of it.' The NASB 1995 captures the force: he has become too full of conceit to detect or hate his own sin. The Hebrew word chalaq (smooth, flattering) describes the condition of a person whose self-regard has become so polished that sin cannot gain traction in his conscience. This is not the repentant believer struggling with indwelling sin; this is someone in whom the sin-detection mechanism has been actively disabled by cultivated self-approval. Jeremiah 17:9 ('the heart is more deceitful than all else') and Romans 1:21-22 ('they became futile in their speculations, and their foolish heart was darkened') give the canonical context. The wicked man's great danger is not the gross sin visible to others but the invisible flattery by which he has convinced himself that his iniquity does not exist. This makes Psalm 36 a warning for every person who uses a sophisticated vocabulary of self-understanding to avoid the simpler work of confession."
