          "title": "The shadow of wings and the river of delights",
          "body": "Verses 7-9 move from cosmic description to intimate invitation. 'How precious is Your lovingkindness, O God!' — the exclamation marks a shift from argument to adoration. The children of men take refuge in the shadow of His wings (36:7), an image that runs through the Psalter (17:8; 57:1; 61:4; 91:4) and carries with it the maternal warmth of a protecting parent. In that refuge they drink their fill of the abundance of His house (36:8) and are given to drink of the river of His delights. The word for 'delights' is eden — the very word embedded in the garden's name (Genesis 2:8). David frames God's sanctuary not as an upgrade but as a restoration; the river flowing from God's house is the river of Eden that the fall interrupted, now available again to those who take refuge. Verse 9 provides the theological foundation: 'for with You is the fountain of life; in Your light we see light.' God is not a distributor of life resources — He is the fountain, the maqor, the unoriginated spring. And the epistemological corollary is equally stunning: the capacity to perceive reality rightly ('we see light') is itself mediated by God's own light. Augustine's famous formulation — 'Thou madest us for Thyself' — is the theological echo of verse 9: the creature cannot know or live apart from the Creator as the ground of both."
