          "body": "Verses 10-12 press the psalm's theology into prayer. The doxology of verses 5-9 has not been abstract liturgy; it has been building the ground for personal petition. David asks God to 'continue' (mashakh — draw out, extend) His lovingkindness to those who know Him and His righteousness to the upright in heart. The prayer is striking for what it does not ask: it does not ask God to become something He has not been; it asks Him to persist in what He already is. The very immutability celebrated in the doxology is the ground of confidence in the petition. Verse 11 narrows the request to David's own situation: let not the foot of pride come upon me, let not the hand of the wicked drive me away. The abstract categories of 'the wicked man' (vv. 1-4) now have a foot and a hand that threaten the psalmist personally. The psalm closes in verse 12 with oracular finality: 'there the doers of iniquity have fallen; they have been thrust down and cannot rise.' The three perfect-tense verbs — fallen, thrust down, cannot rise — are prophetic perfects, stating the destruction of the wicked with the certainty of something already accomplished. The same voice that opened with 'an oracle (neum)' about transgression closes with a verdict as certain as a completed event. The wicked man's inner oracle was a lie; the Lord's verdict is the truth."
